WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.129 --> 00:00:03.843
In the other demos we showed malware that needed the user

2
00:00:03.871 --> 00:00:06.585
to run a malicious file in order to be active. 

3
00:00:06.785 --> 00:00:08.530
But worms work differently.

4
00:00:08.730 --> 00:00:11.644
In this demo, we're showing how some types of malware

5
00:00:11.844 --> 00:00:12.443
like worms

6
00:00:12.643 --> 00:00:13.884
 can spread on their own

7
00:00:14.084 --> 00:00:15.518
across a network

8
00:00:15.718 --> 00:00:18.924
without the user clicking anything or opening any program.

9
00:00:20.757 --> 00:00:22.989
The malware starts by scanning the network.

10
00:00:23.189 --> 00:00:24.714
It looks for active devices

11
00:00:24.914 --> 00:00:27.003
 checks which ones are reachable

12
00:00:27.203 --> 00:00:28.762
and then tests for open ports.

13
00:00:32.143 --> 00:00:35.410
When it finds a device with weak or default credentials

14
00:00:35.610 --> 00:00:38.391
the worm sends its malicious code automatically.

15
00:00:38.591 --> 00:00:40.246
No user action is needed

16
00:00:40.446 --> 00:00:42.241
Now we can see that the worm

17
00:00:42.271 --> 00:00:43.981
successfully delivered the payload

18
00:00:44.300 --> 00:00:46.492
but nothing shows up on the victim device

19
00:00:47.543 --> 00:00:49.148
This is an important point

20
00:00:49.173 --> 00:00:52.444
Some malware can enter your device quietly

21
00:00:52.471 --> 00:00:54.943
and stay hidden until it is triggered

22
00:00:55.143 --> 00:00:57.121
The trigger could be a specific action

23
00:00:57.321 --> 00:01:00.736
a certain time, or another condition set by the attacker

24
00:01:00.936 --> 00:01:03.904
In our simulation, the trigger is simple

25
00:01:04.104 --> 00:01:07.457
The malware activates when the user restarts their device.

